quran[21]{c,v,t,f}:
100,10,"and the secrets of the hearts are laid bare (and examined)? {1}",footnotes:1:That is all the intentions
100,11,"Surely on that Day will their Lord be fully informed about them. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
101,1,"The Calamity! {1}",footnotes:1:Qariah literally means the striking one. Qar is to strike one thing upon another so severely as to produce a noise. In view of this literal meaning
101,2,"What is the Calamity?"
101,3,"And what do you know what the Calamity is?"
101,4,"On that Day human beings shall be like scattered moths,"
101,5,"and the mountains shall be like fluffs of carded wool in varying colours. {1}",footnotes:1:This will be the first stage of Resurrection
101,6,"Then {1} he whose scales weigh heavier",footnotes:1:From here begins description of the second stage of Resurrection when after having been resurrected men will appear in the court of God.
101,7,"shall have a blissful life;"
101,8,"but he whose scales weigh lighter, {1}",footnotes:1:The word mawazin in the original can be plural of mauzun as well as
101,9,"his shall be the deep pit for a dwelling. {1}",footnotes:1:The words in the original are: ummu hu hawiyah: his mother will be hawiyah. Hawiyah is from hawa
101,10,"And what do you know what that is?"
101,11,"A Blazing Fire! {1}",footnotes:1:That is
102,1,"The craving for ever-greater worldly gains and to excel others in that regard keeps you occupied {1}",footnotes:1:The words alhakum at-takathur of the original are too vast in meaning to be fully explained in a passage. Alhakum is from lahv which originally means heedlessness
102,2,"until you reach your graves. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
102,3,"Nay, you will soon come to know; {1}",footnotes:1:That is
102,4,"nay, again, you shall soon come to know."
102,5,"Nay, would that you knew with certainty of knowledge (what your attitude will lead to, you would never have acted the way you do)."
102,6,"You will surely end up seeing Hell;"
102,7,"again, you shall most certainly end up seeing it with absolute certainty."
102,8,"Then, on that Day, you will be called to account for all the bounties you enjoyed. {1}",footnotes:1:“Then” in this sentence does not mean that accountability will be held after the culprits have been cast into Hell
